## Purpose
In a codebase maintained by multiple agents and developers across years, naming is a discoverability and communication tool.
This rule encodes Forkumentos-specific naming decisions, not generic Dart conventions. Dart conventions are assumed knowledge.

## Scope
Any new identifier: file names, class names, provider names, method names, parameters, enum cases, asset filenames.

## Core Principles
- A name is correct when, given the name alone, a developer can locate the file and understand its purpose without searching.
- Abbreviations are prohibited unless the abbreviation is universally known and shorter is unambiguously clearer (e.g., `id` is acceptable; `mgr`, `cfg`, `svc` are not).
- Model classes are named after their domain concept without technological suffixes: `Project`, not `ProjectModel` or `ProjectEntity`.
- Feature-scoped classes carry the feature name as a prefix only when disambiguation is necessary: `MappingColumn` (not just `Column`), but `Template` (not `DocumentTemplate`) unless `Template` is ambiguous at the call site.
- Riverpod providers are named `[concept][Layer]Provider`: `mappingStateProvider`, `activeProjectProvider`, `templateListProvider`.

## DO
- Name files after their primary exported class, in `snake_case`: `mapping_column.dart` exports `MappingColumn`.
- Name test files after the file under test with a `_test` suffix: `mapping_column_test.dart`.
- Use `PascalCase` for classes, enums, typedefs, extensions.
- Use `camelCase` for variables, methods, parameters, and provider identifiers.
- Use `snake_case` for file names, folder names, and all asset filenames.

## DON'T
- Name a class `Manager`, `Handler`, `Helper`, or `Util` â€” these names describe nothing about the domain.
- Use the word `data` as a class name or variable name without a domain qualifier (`sourceData` is acceptable; `data` alone is not).
- Suffix providers with `Notifier` when they are accessed from the UI â€” the provider is accessed, not the notifier.

## NEVER
- Give two classes in the same domain layer names that differ only by suffix (e.g., `TemplateModel` and `Template` coexisting).
- Name a file after a pattern (`base_repository.dart`) when it contains a domain concept (`template_repository.dart`).

## GOOD Example
```dart
// Provider name: concept + layer + Provider
final activeProjectProvider = StateNotifierProvider<ActiveProjectNotifier, Project?>(...);

// Class name: domain concept, no suffix
class MappingColumn { ... }
```

## BAD Example
```dart
// Vague provider name
final stateProvider = ...;

// Technological suffix on a model
class ProjectModel { ... }
```

## Decision Rules
Is there already a class with a similar name in the same layer? â†’ Disambiguate with a feature prefix.
Is the name a verb? â†’ It is a method. Classes are nouns or noun phrases.
Does the name describe the technology rather than the domain? â†’ Rename it.

## Conflict Resolution
This rule is self-contained. No other rule overrides naming decisions. ARCHITECTURE.md folder names take precedence over file naming conventions when they conflict.
